org.pimslims.business.crystallization.model
Class WellPosition

java.lang.Object
  org.pimslims.business.crystallization.model.WellPosition
All Implemented Interfaces:
java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>
public class WellPosition
    
extends java.lang.Object

    
implements java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>





Class to describe the position of a trial drop within a trial plate.
WellPosition is immutable.



Note that row, column and subPosition are one-based and that a
WellPosition with row = 1, column = 1 and subPosition = 1 will return "A01.1"
from a call to the toString() method.



If using the WellPosition(String)
constructor, the name is first converted to upper case and then the row and
column numbers are parsed using the pattern "^([A-Z]+)(\d+)(\.\d+)?$". The row
is assumed to be encoded in base 26 in the alphabetic component and the column
given by the numeric component. When using this constructor, the row is A-based
and the column and subPosition 1-based, i.e. the name "A01.1" will be parsed to
row = 1, column = 1 and subPosition = 1.



If constructed using WellPosition(String),
the WellPosition will remember the name specified in the constructor and will
return it when toString()
is called, though not when toStringNoSubPosition()
is called. Note that the name is not used in equality testing or hashcode
calculation.



This implementation means that equivalent WellPositions can be parsed
from many different names. For example, the following are all equal:





     WellPosition wp1 = new WellPosition("A1");
     WellPosition wp2 = new WellPosition("A01");
     WellPosition wp3 = new WellPosition("A0001");
     WellPosition wp4 = new WellPosition("A1.1");
     WellPosition wp5 = new WellPosition("A01.01");

formatName


public static java.lang.String formatName(int row,
                                          int column,
                                          int subPosition)



    

    
Format the name from the row, column and subPosition. The row is
    encoded in base 26. The column and subPosition are used as given, with the
    subPosition separated from the column by a '.'. If subPosition is < 1 then
    both it and the separator will be omitted. The formatted name conforms to NAME_PATTERN
    and can be parsed by parseName(String).

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

        
Parameters:

        
row - - the row

        
column - - the column

        
subPosition - - the subPosition

        
Returns:

        
The name

    

    








parseName


public static int[] parseName(java.lang.String name)



    

    
Parse the row and column from a name. The name must match NAME_PATTERN,
    otherwise an IllegalArgumentException is thrown. The row is assumed to be
    encoded in base 26 in the initial alphabetic part of the name. The column is
    given by the subsequent numeric part. The subPosition is separated from the
    column by a '.'. If no subPosition is specified, it is assumed to be 1.


    
Returns a three-element array of int containing the row, column and
    subPosition as elements 0, 1 and 2 respectively.

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

    

        
Parameters:

        
name - - the name to parse

        
Returns:

        
int[] {row, column, subposition}

        
Throws:

        
java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the name
        does not match NAME_PATTERN
